        "as-1": {
          "type": "article_section",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "The Basics: What Happens When You Lacto-Ferment",
            "anchor_id": "section-1",
            "body": "<p>Lacto-fermentation is a controlled bacterial process. You combine vegetables with salt and water, then wait. The naturally-occurring lactic acid bacteria — which live on every vegetable surface — start eating the sugars in the food and producing lactic acid. The acid drops the pH low enough that harmful bacteria can't survive, while the good bacteria thrive.</p><p>There's no heat. No starter culture needed. No special equipment beyond a jar. The bacteria do all the work. What you get back is food that's preserved for months, packed with live probiotics, with a tang that comes from real lactic acid (the same compound that makes yogurt sour, or your muscles ache after a hard run).</p><p>This is how humans preserved cabbage in Korea, mangoes in Punjab, cucumbers in Eastern Europe, and milk everywhere — for thousands of years before refrigeration existed.</p>"
          }
        },
        "article_section_HPE6Bg": {
          "type": "article_section",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Why Salt Matters (And the Right Ratio)",
            "anchor_id": "",
            "body": "<p>Salt is the gatekeeper. At 2% salt by weight, harmful bacteria (Listeria, E. coli, Salmonella) can't reproduce. But lactic acid bacteria can. So salt creates a controlled environment where only the good guys grow.</p><p>Get the ratio wrong and the whole thing fails. Too little salt and bad bacteria take over — your jar smells like death and you throw it out. Too much salt and even the good bacteria struggle — fermentation stalls, the vegetables stay raw and sharp.</p><p>For most ferments: 2% salt by weight of the vegetables. That's 20 grams of salt per kilogram of cabbage. Use a kitchen scale. Don't eyeball it.</p>"
          }
        },
        "pull_quote_EAgPQd": {
          "type": "pull_quote",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><em><strong>Salt is not a flavoring in fermentation. It's a referee. Without it, the wrong team wins.</strong></em></p>"
          }
        }
      },
